'''{{ill|Komoriyama Kofun|ja|小盛山古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Komoriyama Kofun|qq=}}''' (小盛山古墳) is a {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Kofun|qq=}} (ancient Kofun) located in {{ill|Kita-ku (Okayama)|ja|北区|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kita-ku (Okayama)|qq=}}, {{ill|Okayama|ja|岡山市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okayama|qq=}}, {{ill|Okayama Prefecture|ja|岡山県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okayama Prefecture|qq=}}. It is a round tumulus and is not Historic Site1 as a historic site.

This tumulus Ranks as the third-largest round tumulus in Japan.<ref group="Note" name="map_size">The main round tumuli in Japan are as follows:
# {{ill|Tomio Maruyama Kofun|ja|富雄丸山古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tomio Maruyama Kofun|qq=}} ({{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara Prefecture|qq=}} {{ill|Nara|ja|奈良市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara|qq=}}) - Diameter: 109 meters.
# {{ill|Maruhakayama Kofun|ja|丸墓山古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Maruhakayama Kofun|qq=}} ({{ill|Saitama Prefecture|ja|埼玉県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saitama Prefecture|qq=}} {{ill|Gyōda|ja|行田市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gyōda|qq=}}) - Diameter: 105 meters.
# '''Komoriyama Kofun''' (Okayama, Okayama Prefecture) - Diameter: 95 meters.</ref> It is also known as "Tsukuriyama Kofun" (造山古墳), though it is distinct from the {{ill|Tsukuriyama Kofun (Okayama)|lt=Tsukuriyama Kofun|ja|造山古墳|1=Tsukuriyama Kofun (Okayama)|lt=Tsukuriyama Kofun|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsukuriyama Kofun (Okayama)|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsukuriyama Kofun (Okayama)|qq=}} in Shinjo-shimo, Kita-ku, Okayama City.{{Sfn|Komoriyama Kofun (Heibonsha)|1988}}

== Overview ==

Komoriyama Kofun is a large round tumulus constructed at the edge of a hill on the western side of Okayama City.{{Sfn|Komoriyama Kofun (Heibonsha)|1988}} Its type is circular and includes a {{ill|Tsukuridashi|ja|造出|1=Platform-style projection|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsukuridashi|13=User:Immanuelle/Platform-style projection|qq=}} (a projecting plattype).<ref name="Okayama City"/> The mound is built in three tiers, while the tsukuridashi is built in two tiers.<ref name="Okayama City"/> The diameter of the mound is 95 meters, and the total length, including the tsukuridashi, is 108 meters,<ref name="Okayama City"/> making it the third-largest round tumulus in Japan.<ref group="Note" name="map_size"/> 

Haniwa and paving stones have been identified on the surface of the mound.<ref name="Okayama City"/> Four reservoirs surrounding the mound are believed to be remnants of a surrounding moat, though details remain unclear.<ref name="Okayama City"/> The burial facility itself is unknown.{{Sfn|Komoriyama Kofun (Heibonsha)|1988}}

The tumulus is estimated to have been constructed in the latter half of the {{ill|4th century|ja|4世紀|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/4th century|qq=}}, during the latter part of the {{ill|Early Kofun period|ja|古墳時代前期|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Early Kofun period|qq=}}.<ref name="Okayama City">[http://www.city.okayama.jp/museum/kofun1/10.html Komoriyama Kofun] (Okayama City Museum "Explore Okayama's Historic Site").</ref> Among early period round tumuli, it Ranks as the largest in Japan.<ref name="Okayama City"/> 

In the Kibi region, preceding tumuli such as {{ill|Onoe Kurumayama Kofun|ja|尾上車山古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onoe Kurumayama Kofun|qq=}} and {{ill|Nakayama Chausuyama Kofun|ja|中山茶臼山古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakayama Chausuyama Kofun|qq=}} are known for being located on hilltops overlooking the sea. In contrast, Komoriyama Kofun's location differs, drawing academic attention.<ref name="Okayama City"/> It is speculated that the lineage of local chieftain burials transitioned from this kofun to later tumuli such as {{ill|Sakotadōyama Kofun|ja|佐古田堂山古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakotadōyama Kofun|qq=}} and Tsukuriyama Kofun.<ref>[http://www.city.okayama.jp/museum/kofun2/02.html Sakotadōyama Kofun] (Okayama City Museum "Explore Okayama's Historic Site").</ref>

