# '''Komoriyama Kofun''' (Okayama, Okayama Prefecture) - Diameter: 95 meters.</ref> It is also known as "Tsukuriyama Kofun" (造山古墳), though it is distinct from the [[:en:Tsukuriyama Kofun (Okayama)|Tsukuriyama Kofun]] in Shinjo-shimo, Kita-ku, Okayama City.{{Sfn|Komoriyama Kofun (Heibonsha)|1988}}

== Overview ==

Komoriyama Kofun is a large round tumulus constructed at the edge of a hill on the western side of Okayama City.{{Sfn|Komoriyama Kofun (Heibonsha)|1988}} Its type is circular and includes a {{ill|Tsukuridashi|ja|造出|1=Platform-style projection|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsukuridashi|13=User:Immanuelle/Platform-style projection|qq=}} (a projecting plattype).<ref name="Okayama City"/> The mound is built in three tiers, while the tsukuridashi is built in two tiers.<ref name="Okayama City"/> The diameter of the mound is 95 meters, and the total length, including the tsukuridashi, is 108 meters,<ref name="Okayama City"/> making it the third-largest round tumulus in Japan.<ref group="Note" name="map_size"/> 

Haniwa and paving stones have been identified on the surface of the mound.<ref name="Okayama City"/> Four reservoirs surrounding the mound are believed to be remnants of a surrounding moat, though details remain unclear.<ref name="Okayama City"/> The burial facility itself is unknown.{{Sfn|Komoriyama Kofun (Heibonsha)|1988}}

The tumulus is estimated to have been constructed in the latter half of the [[:en:4th century|4th century]], during the latter part of the {{ill|Early Kofun period|ja|古墳時代前期|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Early Kofun period|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}.<ref name="Okayama City">[http://www.city.okayama.jp/museum/kofun1/10.html Komoriyama Kofun] (Okayama City Museum "Explore Okayama's Historic Site").</ref> Among early period round tumuli, it Ranks as the largest in Japan.<ref name="Okayama City"/> 

In the Kibi region, preceding tumuli such as [[:en:Onoe Kurumayama Kofun|Onoe Kurumayama Kofun]] and {{ill|Nakayama Chausuyama Kofun|ja|中山茶臼山古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakayama Chausuyama Kofun|qq=}} are known for being located on hilltops overlooking the sea. In contrast, Komoriyama Kofun's location differs, drawing academic attention.<ref name="Okayama City"/> It is speculated that the lineage of local chieftain burials transitioned from this kofun to later tumuli such as {{ill|Sakotadōyama Kofun|ja|佐古田堂山古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakotadōyama Kofun|qq=}} and Tsukuriyama Kofun.<ref>[http://www.city.okayama.jp/museum/kofun2/02.html Sakotadōyama Kofun] (Okayama City Museum "Explore Okayama's Historic Site").</ref>

